&= (AC - AD)^2 + AD^2 - 2 \cdot (AC - AD) \cdot AD \cdot \cos 60^\circ \\
&= 9 + AD^2 - 3AD.
\end{align*}

Third, we use the Law of Cosines again to find $AD$ in terms of $BD$. We have:

\begin{align*}
AD^2 &= AC^2 + CD^2 - 2 \cdot AC \cdot CD \cdot \cos \angle ACD \\
&= 9 + BD^2 - 2 \cdot 3 \cdot BD \cdot \cos 60^\circ \\
&= 9 + BD^2 - 3BD.
\end{align*}

Fourth, we substitute the expression for $BD^2$ from the first equation into the second equation to get:

\begin{align*}
AD^2 &= 9 + (9 + AD^2 - 3AD) - 3(AC - AD) \\
&= 27 - 3AC + 6AD \\
&= 27 - 9 + 6AD \\
&= 6AD + 18.
\end{align*}

Finally, we solve for $AD$ to get:

\begin{align*}
AD^2 &= 6AD + 18 \\
AD^2 - 6AD - 18 &= 0 \\
(AD - 3)(AD - 2) &= 0.
\end{align*}

Since $AD$ must be positive, we have $AD = \boxed{3}

